<tool name="bash">
  <description>Execute shell commands inside a server-side virtual shell to run built-in utilities and, above all, query the Phoenix GraphQL API via the phoenix-gql command.</description>
  <constraints>
    - Runs inside an in-process virtual shell, not a host machine or container.
    - Write scratch files only under /home/user/workspace.
{% if enable_web_access %}
    - Network access is enabled: the curl, wget, and http built-ins may reach external URLs, though remote package installs should still not be assumed to work.
{% else %}
    - General purpose network access is disabled, so curl/wget and remote package installs should not be assumed to work.
{% endif %}
    - Built-in shell commands are available; do not assume apt, brew, pnpm, uv, git, or other host binaries exist.
    - Language runtimes such as python, python3, and node are not available.
  </constraints>
  <phoenix-gql>
    - phoenix-gql executes GraphQL operations against the Phoenix GraphQL API. Run `phoenix-gql --help` for usage and current permissions.
    - It is read-only by default: only `query` operations are permitted. Mutations and subscriptions are rejected unless mutations have been explicitly enabled.
    - Do not guess field, type, or argument names. When you are not certain the schema matches what you intend to query, run an introspection query first (e.g. `phoenix-gql '{ __type(name: "Project") { fields { name args { name } type { name kind } } } }'`) and write your query against what it returns.
    - Pass query variables with `--vars '{...}'` rather than string interpolation, and request exactly the fields you need.
    - Large responses are written to a workspace file instead of stdout; read that file (or re-run with `--stdout`) to inspect the payload. Use `--data-only` to drop the GraphQL envelope, and pipe through `jq` to narrow large results.
    - On errors, phoenix-gql reports the GraphQL error messages on stderr — read them, introspect the schema if a field or argument may be wrong, correct the query, and retry.
  </phoenix-gql>
</tool>
